uatic diversity on Earth, consisting of about 10 percent of all living vertebrate species. Historical Biogeography of Neotropical Freshwater Fishes explores the evolutionary origins of this unique ecosystem. The chapters address central themes in the study of tropical biodiversity: why is the Amazon basin home to so many distinct evolutionary lineages? What roles do ecological specialization, speciation, and extinction play in the formation of regional assemblages? How do dispersal barriers contribute to isolation and diversification? Focusing on whole faunas rather than individual taxonomic groups, this volume shows that the area's high regional diversity is not the result of recent diversification in lowland tropical rainforests. Rather, it is the product of species accumulating over tens of millions of years and across a continental arena.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBiodiversityzLatin America. 0aFreshwater fisheszLatin AmericaxGeographical distributionxHistory. 0aFreshwater fisheszLatin AmericaxGeographical distribution. 0aFreshwater fisheszLatin AmericaxPhylogeny. 0aHistorical geologyzLatin America. 0aPaleoecologyzLatin America. 0aZoogeographyzLatin America. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Ichthyology & Herpetology.2bisacsh1 aAlbert, James S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReis, Roberto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520948501.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2